      "id": 354252,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>We’ll see in Chapter 11 that alkyl halides react with hydrosulfide ion (HS<sup>−</sup>) to give a product whose stereochemistry is inverted from that of the reactant.</p>\n<p>Draw the reaction of (<i>S</i>)-2-bromobutane with HS<sup>−</sup> ion to yield 2-butanethiol, CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>CH(SH)CH<sub>3</sub>. Is the stereochemistry of the product <i>R</i> or <i>S</i>?</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down-30\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBcFVSIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--5d73e714b12f40b679d26884450993c8868dfa15/OChem_05_EC_031.jpg\" alt=\"The figure shows a reaction where an alkyl bromide reacts with H S anion  to form a thiol compound and a bromide ion.\">",
